7
00:00:34,320 --> 00:00:38,431
What is the Gartley pattern?

8
00:00:38,431 --> 00:00:43,891
The Gartley pattern resembles an M/W shape
on the chart, depending on whether it is a

9
00:00:43,891 --> 00:00:47,600
bullish or a bearish Gartley and consists
of five points on the chart.

10
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:52,010
These points are marked with X, A, B, C, and
D.

11
00:00:52,010 --> 00:00:57,110
Gartley is a retracement and continuation
pattern at the same time, depending on its

12
00:00:57,110 --> 00:01:02,670
location in a trend, that is formed when a
trend temporarily changes direction before

13
00:01:02,670 --> 00:01:05,010
continuing in its original direction.

14
00:01:05,010 --> 00:01:10,850
And it provides a low-risk opportunity for
traders to enter the market where the pattern

15
00:01:10,850 --> 00:01:14,340
finishes and the trend comes back.

16
00:01:14,340 --> 00:01:19,781
How to identify the Gartley pattern?

17
00:01:19,781 --> 00:01:22,940
The Gartley pattern depends on several movements
in price.

18
00:01:22,940 --> 00:01:26,200
Every swing has to confirm certain Fibonacci
levels.

19
00:01:26,200 --> 00:01:30,250
To make it very simple, let’s look at each
component of the Gartley structure.

20
00:01:30,250 --> 00:01:33,990
X to A swing
The movement begins with X to A and there

21
00:01:33,990 --> 00:01:35,869
are no specifics for this leg.

22
00:01:35,869 --> 00:01:41,950
This first leg gets formed when the price
sharply rises or declines from point X to

23
00:01:41,950 --> 00:01:43,039
point A.

24
00:01:43,039 --> 00:01:46,310
This is the longest leg of the pattern.

25
00:01:46,310 --> 00:01:50,270
A to B swing
This is where Fibonacci becomes relevant to

26
00:01:50,270 --> 00:01:51,389
the pattern.

27
00:01:51,389 --> 00:01:57,120
The A-B leg will not retrace pass point X
– if it does, the pattern is considered

28
00:01:57,120 --> 00:01:58,299
invalid.

29
00:01:58,299 --> 00:02:03,119
The AB swing should be approximately 61.8%
of the XA leg.

30
00:02:03,119 --> 00:02:10,750
B to C swing
This movement should be a retracement of 38.2%

31
00:02:10,750 --> 00:02:19,570
or 88.6% of the movement of A to B. If the
B to C move retraces above point A, the Gartley

32
00:02:19,570 --> 00:02:20,570
pattern is invalid.

33
00:02:20,570 --> 00:02:26,270
C to D swing
This should be an extension of the B to C

34
00:02:26,270 --> 00:02:27,270
leg.

35
00:02:27,270 --> 00:02:35,530
If BC is 38.2% of AB, then CD should respond
to the 127.2% extension of BC.

36
00:02:35,530 --> 00:02:44,510
If BC is 88.6% of AB, then CD leg should be
the 161.8% extension of BC swing.

37
00:02:44,510 --> 00:02:48,700
A to D swing
After the completion of C-D, you measure the

38
00:02:48,700 --> 00:02:55,510
overall movement of A to D. It should be a
78.6 percent retracement of the change in

39
00:02:55,510 --> 00:03:00,500
price of X to A.
I know it might seem complicated at first,

40
00:03:00,500 --> 00:03:06,580
but if you use Tradingview, you can use this
tool and you can start drawing the pattern.

41
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:09,190
You just need 4 price swings.

42
00:03:09,190 --> 00:03:14,920
Just place the tools at the extreme of the
swings and start backtesting.

43
00:03:14,920 --> 00:03:21,840
Ideal Gartley
The ideal Gartley will be defined by specific

44
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:23,900
Fibonacci retracements.

45
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:31,010
One of the most important numbers in the pattern
is the completion of point D at the 0.786

46
00:03:31,010 --> 00:03:32,820
of XA.

47
00:03:32,820 --> 00:03:37,570
Although the price action might exceed this
number slightly, it should not exceed point

48
00:03:37,570 --> 00:03:38,590
X.

49
00:03:38,590 --> 00:03:44,330
Another important point in the pattern is
the 0.618 retracement of the XA leg.

50
00:03:44,330 --> 00:03:49,190
The AB leg should reverse very close to this
retracement.

51
00:03:49,190 --> 00:03:55,310
The .618 retracement at point B is critical
because it will establish another Fibonacci

52
00:03:55,310 --> 00:04:02,810
projection - usually a 1.27 of BC - in the
Potential Reversal Zone at point D.

53
00:04:02,810 --> 00:04:08,650
The best part about Gartley patterns is that
they indicate both the timing and magnitude

54
00:04:08,650 --> 00:04:10,760
of price movements.

55
00:04:10,760 --> 00:04:18,009
Bullish Gartley Pattern
The Bullish Gartley starts with a bullish

56
00:04:18,009 --> 00:04:19,470
XA move.

57
00:04:19,470 --> 00:04:21,539
AB is then bearish.

58
00:04:21,539 --> 00:04:25,169
BC is bullish, and CD is bearish again.

59
00:04:25,169 --> 00:04:29,620
And you expect a reversal of the CD move.

60
00:04:29,620 --> 00:04:34,650
This means that a bullish Gartley implies
a price increase from Point D.

61
00:04:34,650 --> 00:04:41,629
The full target of the pattern is the 161.8%
Fibonacci extension of the AD move, which

62
00:04:41,629 --> 00:04:45,719
resembles the AB=CD harmonic pattern upon
completion.

63
00:04:45,719 --> 00:04:50,659
And, we have three intermediary targets before
that.

64
00:04:50,659 --> 00:04:55,090
Target 1: B Swing
Target 2: C Swing

65
00:04:55,090 --> 00:04:57,170
Target 3: A Swing

66
00:04:57,170 --> 00:05:06,610
Bearish Gartley Pattern
The bearish Gartley has a bearish XA move,

67
00:05:06,610 --> 00:05:13,100
a bullish AB move, a bearish BC move, and
a bullish CD move.

68
00:05:13,100 --> 00:05:17,520
A bearish Gartley implies a price decrease
from Point D.

69
00:05:17,520 --> 00:05:25,290
The expected price target of the bearish pattern
is the 161.8% extension of the AD move, with

70
00:05:25,290 --> 00:05:29,139
the intermediary targets at swings B, C and
A.

71
00:05:29,139 --> 00:05:37,289
How To Trade Gartley Harmonic Pattern
To enter a Gartley trade you should first

72
00:05:37,289 --> 00:05:41,509
take note of the pattern and then confirm
if it is valid or not.

73
00:05:41,509 --> 00:05:47,150
First, you outline the four price swings on
the chart and you make sure they respond to

74
00:05:47,150 --> 00:05:49,680
their respective Fibonacci levels.

75
00:05:49,680 --> 00:05:55,919
You mark every price action swing with the
important letters X, A, B, C, and D.

76
00:05:55,919 --> 00:06:00,900
By doing this, you will be able to estimate
the overall size of the pattern and get a

77
00:06:00,900 --> 00:06:04,210
clear idea about the parameters.

78
00:06:04,210 --> 00:06:10,180
If you have a bullish Gartley for example,
you open a long trade if CD leg founds support

79
00:06:10,180 --> 00:06:18,169
at 127.2 percent or 161.8 percent Fibonacci
level of the BC move.

80
00:06:18,169 --> 00:06:23,259
You should always use a stop loss order regardless
of your preferred entry signal, to protect

81
00:06:23,259 --> 00:06:26,849
yourself from any rapid or unexpected price
move.

82
00:06:26,849 --> 00:06:31,979
The stop loss order of a bullish Gartley trade
should be found below the X point of the chart

83
00:06:31,979 --> 00:06:33,330
pattern.

84
00:06:33,330 --> 00:06:39,449
For a bearish Gartley, your stop loss order
should be found above the pattern’s X point.

85
00:06:39,449 --> 00:06:45,110
As for take profits, you enter a position
after the bounce at point D and then scale

86
00:06:45,110 --> 00:06:47,559
out at different levels.

87
00:06:47,559 --> 00:06:51,300
Target 1: B Swing
Target 2: C Swing

88
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:59,759
Target 3: A Swing
Target 4: 161.8% of AD

89
00:06:59,759 --> 00:07:04,909
These four levels on the chart are the four
minimum targets of the bullish Gartley.

90
00:07:04,909 --> 00:07:09,580
That doesn’t mean that the bullish trend
will end when the price completes point E.

91
00:07:09,580 --> 00:07:15,919
You are always free to use additional price
action rules or a trailing stop to exit your

92
00:07:15,919 --> 00:07:16,919
trade.

93
00:07:16,919 --> 00:07:22,210
If the price momentum continues to show signs
of strength, you can keep a small portion

94
00:07:22,210 --> 00:07:24,089
of the trade open.

95
00:07:24,089 --> 00:07:30,460
Use price action clues such as trend lines,
support and resistant techniques, candle patterns

96
00:07:30,460 --> 00:07:34,029
and volume to find the right entry and exit
point.

97
00:07:34,029 --> 00:07:39,611
And generally, if the price action shows no
signs of interrupting the new trend, just

98
00:07:39,611 --> 00:07:41,321
stay in the trade for as long as you can.

99
00:07:41,321 --> 00:07:50,219
Gartley after a Strong Price Move
This pattern is even more significant, if

100
00:07:50,219 --> 00:07:52,839
it is preceded by a major price move.

101
00:07:52,839 --> 00:07:58,639
Often, after a major price move, the Gartley
will begin with a strong counter move, which

102
00:07:58,639 --> 00:08:01,389
becomes the X to A leg.

103
00:08:01,389 --> 00:08:06,860
The price will appear to be consolidating,
attempting to stabilize before making another

104
00:08:06,860 --> 00:08:07,869
strong move.

105
00:08:07,869 --> 00:08:14,199
If a Gartley forms after such price action,
from my backtesting, this pattern will prove

106
00:08:14,199 --> 00:08:15,900
to be a substantial opportunity.

107
00:08:15,900 --> 00:08:21,830
In addition, the stop loss required in the
trade will be relatively small relative to

108
00:08:21,830 --> 00:08:23,499
the potential reversal.

109
00:08:23,499 --> 00:08:28,919
The primary reason for this powerful opportunity
is that a successful reversal will resume

110
00:08:28,919 --> 00:08:34,370
the trend that was established by the initial
XA price move.

111
00:08:34,370 --> 00:08:39,560
The Bullish Gartley after a strong sell-off
is a difficult opportunity to perceive.

112
00:08:39,560 --> 00:08:45,100
When the price forms this pattern, it might
seem as if the market is making lower highs,

113
00:08:45,100 --> 00:08:50,260
especially since point C is below point A
after the initial bounce.

114
00:08:50,260 --> 00:08:56,270
However, the pattern is indicating a potential
buy at the Potential Reversal Zone.

115
00:08:56,270 --> 00:09:01,620
The beauty of this set-up is that it requires
a very small amount of risk to see if the

116
00:09:01,620 --> 00:09:03,560
trade will work out.

117
00:09:03,560 --> 00:09:08,940
Since this is an unusually good set-up, the
potential profit is very large in comparison

118
00:09:08,940 --> 00:09:11,420
to the amount needed to be risked.

119
00:09:11,420 --> 00:09:16,440
The stop loss should be placed, of course,
just below X point.

120
00:09:16,440 --> 00:09:20,990
This is a great example of a Gartley after
a severe decline.

121
00:09:20,990 --> 00:09:24,500
The Potential Reversal Zone was very clear.

122
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:28,520
It had three harmonic numbers within a very
narrow range.

123
00:09:28,520 --> 00:09:42,019
AB is 61.8% of XA, BC is 88.6% of AB, CD is
the 161.8% extension of BC.

124
00:09:42,019 --> 00:09:47,220
At the same time, AD is 78.6% of XA.

125
00:09:47,220 --> 00:09:52,460
Since this is a bullish Gartley setup, the
expected price move is to the upside.

126
00:09:52,460 --> 00:10:01,060
For this reason, you would prepare to buy
when CD finishes at the 161.8% of BC and the

127
00:10:01,060 --> 00:10:03,790
price action bounces upwards.

128
00:10:03,790 --> 00:10:07,220
The stop loss would have been placed just
under X point.

129
00:10:07,220 --> 00:10:12,990
You can see that this situation required only
a small stop to risk in exchange for a bigger

130
00:10:12,990 --> 00:10:14,330
gain.

131
00:10:14,330 --> 00:10:19,000
The first target of this long trade is located
at the level of point B.

132
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:23,880
The second target is at point C and it also
gets accomplished.

133
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:29,710
The price action also reaches the level of
point A, which is the next target on the chart.

134
00:10:29,710 --> 00:10:37,210
And our last target, located at the 161.8%
Fibonacci extension of the AD price move.

135
00:10:37,210 --> 00:10:42,011
Bearish Gartley after a Strong Rally

136
00:10:42,011 --> 00:10:47,910
A Bearish Gartley after a strong rally is
a very powerful reversal signal, as well.

137
00:10:47,910 --> 00:10:54,160
Essentially, a market that can’t rally to
new highs after a considerable move usually

138
00:10:54,160 --> 00:10:56,649
indicates serious weakness.

139
00:10:56,649 --> 00:11:00,800
In this example, the pattern forms after a
strong rally.

140
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:06,300
In this set-up, point X is usually an important
high for the price.

141
00:11:06,300 --> 00:11:09,680
The figure starts with a bearish XA move.

142
00:11:09,680 --> 00:11:14,670
AB is then bullish and BC is bearish.

143
00:11:14,670 --> 00:11:19,120
CD then reverses the bearish BC move.

144
00:11:19,120 --> 00:11:24,790
The pattern should complete in an area where
several harmonic projections converge.

145
00:11:24,790 --> 00:11:33,240
AB takes 61.8% of XA.
BC is the 88.6% level of AB.

146
00:11:33,240 --> 00:11:38,240
CD reaches the 161.8% extension of BC.

147
00:11:38,240 --> 00:11:44,490
When the CD move is finished and the price
creates a bearish bounce from the 161.8% extension

148
00:11:44,490 --> 00:11:48,310
of BC, we confirm that the bearish Gartley
is valid.

149
00:11:48,310 --> 00:11:55,680
So a good sell zone is here, placing a stop
loss order above the swing at point X.

150
00:11:55,680 --> 00:11:59,509
The first target at point B gets completed
rapidly.

151
00:11:59,509 --> 00:12:04,700
The next targets located at point C and A,
also reached.

152
00:12:04,700 --> 00:12:09,949
And the final target, located at the 161.8%
extension of the AD move.

153
00:12:09,949 --> 00:12:15,290
The Gartley is a great pattern that occurs
frequently on all time frames, in all types

154
00:12:15,290 --> 00:12:19,100
of markets and is 100% price action based.

155
00:12:19,100 --> 00:12:24,069
The thing that works about Harmonic Patterns
in general is that they use the confluence

156
00:12:24,069 --> 00:12:29,720
method, meaning that they expect reactions
from clusters of certain levels defined by

157
00:12:29,720 --> 00:12:31,990
Fibonacci retracements.

158
00:12:31,990 --> 00:12:37,259
They work because Fibonacci retracements are
used by many traders and their visibility

159
00:12:37,259 --> 00:12:43,589
makes reactions more likely, thus increasing
the predictive power of the patterns.

